ta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"103833","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/103833"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 28-year-old woman presents to the General Practice clinic with concerns about her ability to focus at work. She reports a lifelong history of difficulty concentrating, forgetfulness, and feeling easily distracted. These symptoms have been present since childhood but have become more problematic in her current job as a project manager. She often misses deadlines, loses important documents, and struggles to sit through meetings. Her partner has also noted that she frequently interrupts conversations and has difficulty relaxing. She has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears well with vital signs within normal limits. She is fidgety during the consultation and often loses track of her thoughts mid-sentence.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is most important in confirming a diagnosis of Attention Deficit Hyperactivity Disorder (ADHD) in this patient?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Presence of symptoms for at least six months","Positive response to a stimulant medication trial","Neuropsychological testing results","Family history of ADHD","Normal thyroid function tests"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe most important factor in confirming a diagnosis of Attention Deficit Hyperactivity Disorder (ADHD) in this patient is the \u003Cstrong\u003Epresence of symptoms for at least six months\u003C/strong\u003E. According to the Diagnostic and Statistical Manual of Mental Disorders (DSM-5), ADHD symptoms must persist for at least 6 months to a degree that is inconsistent with developmental level and negatively impacts social and academic/occupational activities. This patient\u0027s lifelong history of symptoms, which have been present since childhood, meets this criterion.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003Efamily history of ADHD\u003C/strong\u003E can be supportive of the diagnosis, as ADHD has a strong genetic component. However, it is not a diagnostic requirement and many individuals with ADHD do not have a known family history of the disorder.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ENormal thyroid function tests\u003C/strong\u003E are important to rule out other potential causes of attention difficulties, such as thyroid dysfunction. However, while these tests may be part of a comprehensive workup, they are not specific to diagnosing ADHD and would not explain the array of symptoms this patient has experienced over her lifetime.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003Epositive response to a stimulant medication trial\u003C/strong\u003E can be supportive of an ADHD diagnosis, but it is not a diagnostic criterion. Some individuals without ADHD may also experience improved focus with stimulants, and medication trials should not be used as a diagnostic tool.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ENeuropsychological testing results\u003C/strong\u003E can provide valuable information about cognitive functioning and may support an ADHD diagnosis, but they are not required for diagnosis according to DSM-5 criteria. Some individuals with ADHD may perform well on these tests despite significant real-world impairment.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIn addition to the duration of symptoms, other important diagnostic criteria for ADHD in adults include the presence of at least five symptoms of inattention and/or hyperactivity-impulsivity, evidence that the symptoms were present before age 12, evidence that the symptoms are present in two or more settings (e.g., home, work, school), and clear evidence that the symptoms interfere with or reduce the quality of social, academic, or occupational functioning. The patient\u0027s description of difficulties at work and in personal relationships, along with the observed symptoms during the consultation, support the diagnosis of ADHD in this case.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["ADHD diagnosis requires symptoms to be present in multiple settings for at least 6 months.","ADHD symptoms must cause significant impairment in social, academic, or occupational functioning.","ADHD diagnosis in adults requires at least 5 symptoms of inattention and/or hyperactivity-impulsivity."],"references":["Edition F. Diagnostic and statistical manual of mental disorders. Am Psychiatric Assoc. 2013;21(21):591-643."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"86257"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14145"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"86257","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/86257"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-05-27T14:38:48+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-05-27T14:39:58+09:30","number":5,"notes":"","plagiarismCheckedAt":"2025-05-27T14:39:21+09:30","plagiarismScore":40.9,"plagiarismReportUrl":"https://emedici-copyleaks.syd1.digitaloceanspaces.com/plagiarism-report-6825-5.pdf?X-Amz-Content-Sha256=UNSIGNED-PAYLOAD\u0026X-Amz-Algorithm=AWS4-HMAC-SHA256\u0026X-Amz-Credential=DO00QAKVE68N83EBLT2J%2F20250929%2Fsyd1%2Fs3%2Faws4_request\u0026X-Amz-Date=20250929T055359Z\u0026X-Amz-SignedHeaders=host\u0026X-Amz-Expires=601200\u0026X-Amz-Signature=0db4a70c9eb890d3f52a235a789071b3adf4d58d1fc7e2df6c6dfbc0ac5f87dd"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6825"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"103833"}},"author":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"12201"}},"generation":{"data":null}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"10","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/10"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udfad","name":"Psychiatry","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-1